# URL Detection Rules (`parseLineToRecord`)

Lines from `.txt` and `.rtf` uploads are classified in strict order:

## Rule 1 — Explicit `http://` or `https://` scheme → URL
Parse with `new URL()`. If it throws or protocol is wrong → text.

## Rule 2 — Any other explicit scheme → text
`ftp:`, `mailto:`, `data:`, etc. are not web links.

## Rule 3 — No scheme → URL only if hostname contains a dot
```js
const potentialHost = trimmed.split('/')[0].split('?')[0].split('#')[0];
if (potentialHost.includes('.')) { /* try https:// prepend */ }
```

**Why the dot rule matters:**  
`new URL('https://ariadna_cooper')` succeeds — the parser treats the whole word as a hostname. Without the dot check, bare usernames, names, and single words are mis-classified as URLs.

| Input | Classified as |
|-------|--------------|
| `https://example.com` | URL ✓ |
| `example.com/path` | URL ✓ (has dot) |
| `ariadna_cooper` | Text ✓ (no dot) |
| `Miss Dxxx` | Text ✓ (no dot, has space) |
| `mailto:a@b.com` | Text ✓ (non-http scheme) |
| `localhost` | Text ✓ (no dot — intentional) |

## Do not relax this rule without updating tests
Tests live in `js/url-utils.test.js`. Run with:
```
node --test js/url-utils.test.js
```
